    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down,</placeName>
                    <date>Nov. 17, 1879.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I have been very glad to read so good a report.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> Three copies have been forwarded to Mr. Farrer (who is already in communication with Ld. Sandon) and I have asked him to consider what can be done.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> A Government official in another office remarked to me that it was very difficult for ministers to decide what to do in such cases as they must be prepared for mere cavillers in the H. of Commons. It would be a great evil if new varieties have to be raised every 4 or 5 years.</p>
<p>I shall be happy to read your remarks on varieties wearing out soon.</p>
<p>I have had to write many letters today— So believe me, | Yours very faithfully | Ch. Darwin.</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See enclosure to <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12322.xml">letter from James Torbitt, 15 November 1879</ref>.</note> 
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1599.xml">Thomas Henry Farrer</ref> and <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_7348.xml">Dudley Francis Stuart Ryder</ref>, Viscount Sandon (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12279.xml">letter from T. H. Farrer, 30 October 1879</ref>, and <ref target="./DCP-LETT-12325.xml">letter to T. H. Farrer, 17 November 1879</ref>).</note>
            
